Author: @DirtyD218
Comment: Yeah I don't agree with this assumption. Or really any of these theories. To me it was merely a boy seeing what has happened to the world around him (maybe not the whole world, then again maybe it is) and wanting to save the world from what is going on. Which is clearly mind control on possibly a global scale. And about the mer-creatures, I don't think he died down in the water when he got caught and he wasn't under mind control. I never even thought of that as a possibility. I thought the whole time we thought they were trying to kill us but finally the one that got him helped him by making him be able to breathe underwater. Just like there were a few scientists trying to help and some trying to stop him. Just like in life. You really think if something like this happened that every single person would be ok with it? No. There'd be some on the inside that would try to fight it also. So no for me this boy is a hero. Not a part of some experiment with him. He saved these people by destroying all those little power conductors and then the big one at the end (which also happened after many of you say was under mind control.) To me that makes no sense. But hey everyone is entitled to their opinion. But to me the boy is a hero and when he got to the bottom of the hill, after all that running and jumping and climbing... He finally got to rest...

Author: @spongeintheshoe
Comment: IтАЩd like to propose another character, who I call the Continuity Lemming. While the Rational Decision-Maker plans for the future, and the Instant Gratification Monkey focuses on the present, the Continuity Lemming looks toward the past. Specifically, it wants to keep doing whatever youтАЩre already doing. After all, if youтАЩre still computing logic, then whatever youтАЩve been doing hasnтАЩt killed you yet. As such, the Lemming will resist any sort of change in behavior just as hard as the Monkey resists doing something that isnтАЩt fun. But if you can fight the Lemming and stay dedicated to a new behavior for long enough, then eventually, that new behavior stops being a new behavior, and just becomes what you were already doing, at which point the Lemming will be just as dedicated to maintaining this new behavior as it was to fighting it. When the Monkey and the Lemming are working together, they can form a seemingly-insurmountable tag team, but if you can get the Lemming on your side, it can be a powerful ally against the MonkeyтАж although it canтАЩt fight the Monkey _for_ you, and if you drop the ball, the Monkey can take advantage of that opening to turn the Lemming against you.

Comment:
Insights:
1. Universal Procrastination: Urban contends that everyone procrastinates in some form, even if they appear organised. When deadlines are absent, the impact is hidden but potentially more harmful.
2. Emotional Toll: Procrastination carries guilt, regret, and a sense of wasted potential, harming personal fulfilment over time.
3. Role of Unstructured Goals: Many deeply important life pursuits (entrepreneurship, health, relationships) lack explicit deadlines, so these can remain perpetually on hold.
4. Self-Awareness: UrbanтАЩs comedic style might mask a more serious point: procrastination can make people passive observers of their own aspirations if they do not consciously intervene.
5. тАЬNon-ProcrastinatorsтАЭ Do Not Exist: Everyone, in some area of life, must wrestle with the impulse to delay or avoid tasks.
